// Tenses in English are verb forms that indicate the time of an action or state—whether it happens in the past, present, or future. However, English tenses are more nuanced, also conveying aspects which show the nature of the action, such as whether it is completed, ongoing, or habitual. The three main times (past, present, future) combined with the simple, continuous, perfect, and perfect continuous aspects create twelve primary tenses.

// The present tenses describe current habits, general truths, or actions happening now. The Present Simple is used for habits and facts ("I work every day," "Water boils at 100°C"). The Present Continuous describes actions in progress at the moment of speaking ("She is reading a book"). The Present Perfect links the past to the present, describing experiences or actions with present results ("I have visited Paris"). The Present Perfect Continuous emphasizes the duration of an action that started in the past and continues to the present ("They have been waiting for an hour").

// The past tenses refer to completed actions. The Past Simple is for finished actions at a specific past time ("He arrived yesterday"). The Past Continuous describes an action that was in progress at a specific moment in the past ("I was sleeping when you called"). The Past Perfect clarifies the order of two past actions, showing which action happened first ("She had left before I arrived"). The Past Perfect Continuous emphasizes the duration of an action that happened before another past action ("I had been studying for two hours before the exam started").

// The future tenses predict or plan for upcoming events. The Future Simple ("will") is for predictions or spontaneous decisions ("It will rain tomorrow"). "Be going to" is for intentions or plans based on present evidence ("I am going to travel next week"). The Future Continuous describes an action that will be in progress at a specific future time ("This time tomorrow, I will be flying to London"). The Future Perfect projects an action that will be completed before a specific future time ("By 2030, I will have graduated"). Mastering these tenses is crucial for conveying accurate meaning about time and the nature of actions, preventing misunderstandings and enabling clear communication about events across different timeframes.''',
