//               '''Sentence structure refers to the logical and grammatical arrangement of words, phrases, and clauses to form a complete thought. A proper sentence in English must contain at least a subject and a predicate. The subject is who or what the sentence is about, and the predicate, which contains the verb, tells something about the subject. Sentences are categorized into four main types based on their structure: simple, compound, complex, and compound-complex.

// A simple sentence consists of one independent clause, containing a single subject and predicate (e.g., "The dog barked"). It expresses one complete idea. A compound sentence contains two or more independent clauses joined by a coordinating conjunction (for, and, nor, but, or, yet, so) or a semicolon (e.g., "I wanted to go shopping, but I didn't have any money"). This structure allows you to connect related ideas of equal importance.

// A complex sentence contains one independent clause and at least one dependent clause. A dependent clause cannot stand alone as a sentence and is introduced by a subordinating conjunction (e.g., because, although, when, if) or a relative pronoun (e.g., who, which, that). For example, "Although it was raining, we decided to go for a walk." This structure is vital for showing the relationship between ideas, such as cause and effect or contrast. Finally, a compound-complex sentence combines at least two independent clauses and one or more dependent clauses (e.g., "I finished my work, which was very tedious, and then I went home").

// Understanding these structures is key to writing with variety and clarity. Using only simple sentences can make writing sound choppy and simplistic, while overusing complex structures can make it convoluted. A good writer skillfully mixes different sentence types to create a engaging and readable rhythm, emphasize important points, and logically connect ideas, thereby effectively guiding the reader through their argument or narrative.

